ce:section.ce:para:
As well-known, the hole mobility could be improved by improving of the P3HT crystallinity [33]. To illuminate the crystallinity development of P3HT, XRD patterns of all P3HT:PCBM layers were recorded and the results are presented in Fig. 5
                     . As seen, all patterns exhibited the peaks of P3HT at around 2θ value of 5.7° assigned to (100) reflection. It could be said that the peak intensities slightly increased. Notably, an increase in the crystallinity of P3HT was observed with the increasing vol% of B-CQDs. The average crystallite sizes of P3HT:PCBM films were calculated from the Scherrer equation using FWHM (given in Table 1
                     ). Clearly, the crystal sizes increased from 3.82 nm to 5.83 nm and 6.05 nm upon addition of 1 vol% and 3 vol% of B-CQDs into photoactive blend, respectively. The biggest crystal size was obtained to be 7.43 nm from the XRD pattern of P3HT:PCBM-5% B-CQDs surface, as expected. These findings are coherent with literature and provide that the charge carrier mobility of P3HT:PCBM layer, thus photovoltaic performance of OSC could be improved by B-CQDs addition. Since CQDs are quasi-spherical nanomaterials organized by crystalline sp2 graphite cores, CQDs could help to enhance the crystallinity [34]. On the other hand, several QDs or nanomaterials has been utilized to maintain phase segregation of the P3HT:PCBM layer with enhanced crystallinity [35,36]. Although, different parameters including solvent type and thermal treatment could be used to enhance the crystallinity of P3HT, same conditions were employed to all devices with and w/o B-CQDs additive in present study. Therefore, it could be said that the crystallinity improvement related to directly B-CQDs addition.
